Test 16

Now the following step is to fix one particle in place, we can set the trap separation to zero, and transform the bistable trap into a harmonic potential to keep the particle in place. Here is a diagram.

This is done with the polydisperse capabilities from icenumerics, although there are some caveats. In case someone wants to go through my suffering, refer to Some notes on simulating polydisperse systems.

Anyhow, we can see the vertices counts for this simulation. We need to note that some vertices might be counted wrongly since the icenumerics routine does weird shenanigans with the boundaries. Additionally my routine is not supported for this case.

This is what we expect. The system goes from 2in/2out to almost the 4in/4out (for reference I put a dashed line at 0.5). This is simply because of the defect from the fixed particle. The tiny bump of the Type VI simply follows the motion from when the interactions change around degrees, it goes back and finally returns to almost a 2in/2out. This is again expected since the particle is fixed and it provokes a defect.

So, now we are supposed to make memories with this. How exactly? idk.
From the video we can see some weird stuff on how the vertices are being counted. Hopefully those artifacts will disappear for bigger systems.

Test 17

Instantaneous quenches on the thermal system.

Sanity checks always are good,

So the vertices counts give this

In the first red part, the field is OFF, so we are seeing only thermal fluctuations. Then the field is turned ON instantaneously and contrary to the bigger system, we only see disorder.


Not really ordered, kind of ordered. Also, once they get stuck they stop moving, so I guess the total force on each particle is greater than thermal fluctuations.
